  "benchmark_id": "base58",
  "description": "Base58 codec modelled on the base58 library (Bitcoin alphabet): decodeInt/encodeInt (integer <-> numeral) and encode/decode (bytes <-> numeral). The decode direction is pinned by a FROZEN POSITIONAL-VALUE ORACLE — decodeInt s equals the Horner fold acc -> acc*58 + idx(c) over the frozen 58-char alphabet, a closed arithmetic value unique on every input, anchored to frozen */+/58 and the frozen alphabet table (NOT to a copyable decode body). The encode direction is pinned by VALUE-AGREEMENT PAIRED WITH CANONICALITY: encodeInt n decodes back to n AND is a canonical numeral (no redundant leading '1' zero digit, the genuine zero apart); canonicality is the load-bearing clause (value-agreement alone admits non-canonical numerals), and spec_encode_int_unique states the resulting uniqueness directly (any canonical numeral of value n equals encodeInt n). The byte codec is pinned by the leading-zero boundary law (leading zero bytes map to literal '1's, the significant suffix is the big-endian integer fed to encodeInt) plus the leading-'1'-count identity. Concrete frozen vectors (golden base58 of known small ints/bytes) pin the alphabet ordering. The byte round-trip is deliberately NOT in the suite as a driver. Everything is discrete Nat/List/String/Bool, no Float, no base58check checksum layer.",
